The most prominent examples include:\n\n1. Calixarenes: Especially the π-rich aromatic calix[4]arenes, which can present a bowl-shaped cavity lined with aromatic rings. These hosts are highly effective at binding alkali metal cations (e.g., K+, Na+) and organic cations (e.g., ammonium ions) via cation-π interactions.\n\n2. Cyclophanes: These are macrocyclic compounds containing two or more aromatic rings held in close proximity. Their rigid, π-rich cavities are ideal for cation-π binding, particularly with alkali metal ions and certain organic cations.\n\n3. Cucurbiturils: While cucurbiturils are often associated with ion-dipole and hydrophobic interactions, their portals are lined with electron-rich carbonyl oxygens and can also participate in cation-π interactions, especially with aromatic guests bearing cationic groups.\n\n4. Pillararenes: These are pillar-shaped macrocycles composed of hydroquinone units. Their electron-rich cavities can bind cationic guests through cation-π interactions, especially in aqueous environments.\n\n5. Aromatic cryptands and other π-rich macrocycles: Some cryptands and related hosts are designed with aromatic panels to enhance cation-π binding selectivity and strength.\n\nIn summary, calixarenes and cyclophanes are the prototypical hosts for cation-π interactions, but pillararenes and certain cryptands also play significant roles. The most prominent examples include:\n\n1. Calixarenes: Especially the π-rich aromatic calix[4]arenes, which can present a bowl-shaped cavity lined with aromatic rings. These hosts are highly effective at binding alkali metal cations (e.g., K+, Na+) and organic cations (e.g., ammonium ions) via cation-π interactions.\n\n2. Cyclophanes: These are macrocyclic compounds containing two or more aromatic rings held in close proximity. Their rigid, π-rich cavities are ideal for cation-π binding, particularly with alkali metal ions and certain organic cations.\n\n3. Cucurbiturils: While cucurbiturils are often associated with ion-dipole and hydrophobic interactions, their portals are lined with electron-rich carbonyl oxygens and can also participate in cation-π interactions, especially with aromatic guests bearing cationic groups.\n\n4. Pillararenes: These are pillar-shaped macrocycles composed of hydroquinone units. Their electron-rich cavities can bind cationic guests through cation-π interactions, especially in aqueous environments.\n\n5. Aromatic cryptands and other π-rich macrocycles: Some cryptands and related hosts are designed with aromatic panels to enhance cation-π binding selectivity and strength.\n\nIn summary, calixarenes and cyclophanes are the prototypical hosts for cation-π interactions, but pillararenes and certain cryptands also play significant roles.
